# Turing Machine

A **Turing machine** is a mathematical model of computation describing an abstract machine[^turing1936]. It manipulates symbols on a strip of tape according to a table of rules.

[TOC:2-4]

## History

The concept was introduced by *Alan Turing* in 1936 in his paper "On Computable Numbers"[^turing1936]. The machine was designed to formalize the concept of an algorithm.

Despite its simplicity, a Turing machine can simulate any computer algorithm, no matter how complex. This is the basis of the **Church-Turing thesis**[^church].

## Formal Definition {#formal-def}

A Turing machine is a 7-tuple $M = (Q, \Sigma, \Gamma, \delta, q_0, q_{accept}, q_{reject})$ where:

- $Q$ is a finite set of states
- $\Sigma$ is the input alphabet
- $\Gamma$ is the tape alphabet
- $\delta$ is the transition function
- $q_0$ is the start state
- $q_{accept}$ is the accept state
- $q_{reject}$ is the reject state

## Variants

### Multi-tape Turing Machine

A multi-tape machine uses $k$ tapes, each with its own head. It has been proven that any multi-tape machine can be simulated by a single-tape machine.

### Non-deterministic Turing Machine

A non-deterministic Turing machine (NDTM) can have multiple possible transitions for a given state-symbol pair.

## Significance

| Property | Turing Machine | Finite Automaton |
| --- | :---: | :---: |
| Memory | Infinite tape | No memory |
| Power | Universal | Limited |
| Decidability | Halting problem | Always halts |

